     .... his mouth and lips covered by crumbs and traces, his cheek inflated, holding a cookie in his hand*<br>
<br>
 &quot;ghmplf hmplff...&quot;<br>
<br>
 *finishing his mouthful, he swallowed a generous amount of the stout the lady offered, coughed politely and stood on the table*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Just a second, as i said.<br>
  My thanks, for participating to the debate, dark one. But pray hear my words correctly, friend.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *walking left and right, he started moving his hands in rythm with the flow of his words, half lost in his thoughts*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Abbil, if i can allow myself to call you as such, you misheard me.<br>
  Did i actually say one couldn't choose to align himself on a perticular emotion, feeling?<br>
  Nay, i said none could say one feeling or the other cannot exist in him, or that he can utterly and completely close his soul to one of the various feeling composing all of us.<br>
  Aye, fate and destiny's actions can make one more prone as to pick one of the many directions he could, following his need. As you say, the wounded shall praise Rodcet Nife if he believes in salvation, or Bertoxxulous to thank him if he believes in the power of decay. Are those two different?<br>
 No, the Rodcetian feels hope, for cure and health. The bertoxxulian hopes for a chance to propagate what ails him, and mayhaps for survival, albeit not a disfigured and marked by death and rot one, so that he can keep propagating the word of Plague.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *stopping and turning on his heels to face the tier'dal, he tilted his head sideways, crossing his arms*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Now now now, have i been patronizing? I do think not.<br>
  Tier'dals wouldn't find hatred ebcause of past sufferings? First, i did not speak as a tier'dal in temrs of whining or with sufferings in my mouth. But the very origin of tier'dals is this torture and transformation that was imposed on them. Blessing? Curse? I will not try to give an opinion on this, since i do think tier'dals will always have their opinions on this, and as hurtful as it is to me, i'm forced to accept it.<br>
  But do not dare to tell me tier'dals had not wished all koada'dals had been reached by hatred and reborn in the path of hatred. None would trust this, and it was the point i raised when i dared speak through a tier'dal's voice.<br>
<br>
  Have i been patronizing when speaking of other races, olath uss?<br>
  No. The hunger of the trolls is a perfectly known fact, and as i remember i did not make of them the stupid beasts YOUR people consider them to be? Aye, useful, easily converted to the ways of Hatred, but stupid nonetheless... Do not say the contrary, i've frenquently been walking the streets of Neriak as one of yours&quot;<br>
<br>
 *he grinned, starting again his left-turn-right-turn-left routine on the table's top*<br>
<br>
  &quot;The human? Honor and law is their credo, and my words were the one of more than one human warrior or paladin. Are they always this straight in following law and honor? No, because hatred, envy, fear and all that ails fragile minds reach for them and divert them from the path they took as model.<br>
    You say tier'dals choose their path? Truly?<br>
    Then how come the educationnal system of the dark oens direct them since the cradle to the temple of Innoruuk, and to all the guilds of Neriak that are heavily relied to the Path of Hatred? Tell me, friend, if all your life you had been taught the path of hatred, would you tell me you choosed to follow it?<br>
     And na, na, not that good o'l line about 'but but but but but but but but if i was confronted with the other possibilities, it emans i would have learnt and choosen.'.<br>
    Please, friend. Tier'dals were not idiots, far from it, and i heard the teachings of the Plitouth uss, Innoruuk. You are taught about all the other paths, but through the optic of hatred.<br>
   How can the path of honor be seeming any good to you and help make a choice, when you are taught that such creatures that use the notions of honor are not worth even uttering it's name?<br>
  How can you say knowing the path of fear can help you choose hatred, when you are taught Fear as a force that will help you by appearing in your foes hearts WHEN confronted to your hatred?<br>
  If you are taught Hatred as the root of all powers, how can being confronted to such distorted versions of the other paths, then turning a blind eye on the ones learning their true versions, BECAUSE you were taught otherwise and by, oh of course trustful persons (since they were tier'dals!), how can ye tell me it doesn't PUSH you into the path of Hatred?&quot;<br>
<br>
  *the gnome turned toward the high elf paladin, bowing swiftly to him*<br>
<br>
  &quot;May the one you loved find peace, first.<br>
   Second, friend, I apologize, but sadly must i disagree.<br>
   You choosed not to let hatred enter you. Did you not feel any hatred, even if but for a second? If not the slightest, then my friend you are either uncaring, of to the equal of gods, for only those greater beings are able to feel but what they decide to. Since i consider ye a good man and seemingly someone that loved and was love, i trust you to have felt this flinch of hatred, however small it was, when you discovered the horrid truth.<br>
    You speak about humans, saying they are power and gold driven. Have we never seen any koada'dal seeking to reach for the title of Grandmaster invoker, even by using petty tricks? Nor a captain of garrison reacting all too swiftly to the words of a subordinate that aims at stealing his rank? Nay, nay, friend, the lure of power reaches all races... some good soul like ye seem not to be desiring it, but we all desire it.... be it for good or for wrong. You shall, did or might desire power in order to bring unity, I desire power in order to undo what i consider a mistake of the gods, we all seek power... and money is but a potential form of power, friend, one you can use when you decide to, in it's own boundaries...&quot;<br>
<br>
 *Accepting the glass of wine offered by the elf, he bowed once again to thank him then took a sip, his throat aching a little*<br>
<br>
 &quot;As for Tunare, i do not think she seeks peace. Is there a peace existing between wolves and their preys? Or a peace existing between men and kobolds, wich are part of NAture's cycle nonetheless?<br>
  No, peace is against nature, for all that counts is balance in the cycles, harmony and balance. There must be a top force in the nature's chain, as well as a weakest one, and the top force must be able to be destroyed while the weakest are the one being given the greatest chances to survive, seeing they are the basis of the cycle&quot;<br>
<br>
 *He moved his hands, two small snakes of raw energy appearing between them, and starting a circle where they constantly followed one another's tail*<br>
<br>
 &quot;The weak survives the strong one mostly, but is eaten. The strong one diseappears, but soon shall reappear. Harmony and balance, Nature is steady and unmoving. All parts of Nature evolve, tis why evolution is not supposed to counterbalance the cycle.<br>
    Tis why i do not think Tunare as a goddess of good. She is the goddess of Balance, all that is good upsets this balance just as all that is considered evil does.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *he then turned again toward the tier'dal, and nodded to him.*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Ideals are a choice, elf, and your path of hatred is the ideal you fixed yourself. He choosed to put the stress on such said emotions, just as you did with Hatred, and so will the stronger one survive over the weaker one.... but as i said, Koada'dals cannot think about getting rid of you. For you are a part of this cycle of Nature, and utterly annihilating the tier'dals would be upsetting it's balance. They can lessen you until there is but a male and female among you, and perpetrate the race, but definitely making you diseappear would be destroying their own divinity's beliefs.<br>
<br>
 And in the end, i'd ask: Bartender!!!! got any cookies? finished mine!&quot;<br>
<br>
 *with this did he grab a servant's sleeve as the young boy passed by, and slipped some coins in his hand and some words in his ear, the young man soon bringing to Serenity's table a small note with a handdrawing of her profile, along with a rose, where was written that 'I thank ye for yer assistance and gentle words, fair lady. May yer gods and beliefs watch over ye, it would make a gnome's heart glad.'<br>
  With this did the young tender ask the lady if she wished any drink, for the gnome had payed in advance for anything she mught ask*<br>
<br>
 *And so did Rasslyn sit again, holding his glass of wine high as he smiled to the koada'dal male that offered it to him, and started drinking while drawing little butterflies and empty bottles of milk on his spellbook, a plate of cookies soon brought to him*<br>
