<br>
&quot;The problem,&quot; Severan says, after taking a sip of ale, &quot;is that the world is defined by violence.&quot;  He wipes his lips with a napkin and gives the idealistic peace-keeper a crooked half-smile, all cynicism.  &quot;We kill.  We kill to live.  We kill to grow.  Beasts and bugs, monster and humanoid, the sentient and nonsentient alike.  We grow by giving death... or we hide in our homes, weak as children, green recruits with no power, fit for nothing but to be cut down by our enemies.&quot;<br>
<br>
He takes another drink of ale.  &quot;Not that I have anything against pretty words.  The best songs are full of them.  Pretty words.  Pretty fictions.&quot; <p>-- Severan, warrior.<br>
